# @IBABV01P081B_BEG_WYUAU
VAR_BQSXV08P545A VAR_KHTSV04P307A أخبرنا الشيخ الإمام الحافظ أبو طاهر أحمد بن محمد بن أحمد بن محمد بن إبراهيم أبو البركات محمد بن المنذر بن طيبان وأبو الفوارس عمر بن المبارك الخرقي السلفي ثنا أبو البركات محمد بن عبد الله بن يحيى الوكيل قالوا ثنا أبو القاسم عبد الملك بن محمد بن عبد الله بن بشران قال أخبرنا أبو سهل أحمد بن محمد بن عبد الله بن زياد القطان ثنا محمد بن الجهم السمري ثنا @TR1_YUAU@ يعلي بن عبيد عن محمد بن إسحاق عن الزهري عن قبيصة بن ذؤيب قال قال رسول الله صلى الله عليه وسلم إذا شرب الخمر فاجلدوه فإن عاد فاجلدوه فإن عاد فاجلدوه فإن عاد فاقتلوه فأتي لرسول الله صلى الله عليه وسلم برجل من الأنصار يقال له نعيمان فضربه أربع مرات فرأى المسلمون أن القتل قد أخر وأن الضرب قد وجب. @IBABV01P081B_END_WYUAU
PageV01P081
# @COMMENT: HHMXV07P379A places this in the context of Ibn al-Nuʿmān and TKXXV03P375A quotes a portion of the passage in the biography of al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr (although he appears to suggest that Ibn Isḥāq names him as al-Nuʿaymān). TKXXV03P375A states that Nuʿaymān b. ʿAmr was the younger brother of Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr. Ibn al-Nuʿaymān or al-Nuʿaymān is not mentioned in the redaction of Ibn Hishām. He is sometimes identified as al-Nuʿaymān b. ʿAmr b. Rifāʿah b. al-Ḥārith. According to JWZXV05P277A, al-Nuʿaymān participated in Badr, and all of the famous battles in which Muḥammad fought. He was known to have repeatedly been punished for drinking nabīdh. BKHBV06P431A and TBRCV11P554A mention the account of ʿUqbah b. al-Ḥārith where he describes being ordered by Muḥammad to beat Ibn Nuʿaymān or al-Nuʿaymān with shoes and palm branches for drinking. TKXXV03P375A states he died in during the caliphate of Muʿawīyah but KTHBV08P070A places his death in the year 54. HJRSV06P353A states that Ibn Isḥāq identifies him as al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr and not as al-Nuʿaymān, this follows the comment of Ibn Hishām in vol. 1, 703A. A person identified as al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr is mention twice in the redaction of Ibn Hishām: on vol. 1, 552A he is identified as a Jew who was one of two Rabbis who questioned Muḥammad and then rejected him. On vol. 1, 703A he is identified as al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr b. Rifāʿah b. Sawād, a member of the Sawād b. Mālik b. Ghamm clan, among the Anṣ ār, who participated at Badr. Ibn Hishām, in his commentary, states his name was Nuʿaymān. It is not clear if Ibn Isḥāq understood al-Nuʿmān b. ʿAmr to be the individual who is commonly referred to as being punished for drinking. For passages within the Ibn Isḥāq tradition that identify Nuʿaymān or al-Nuʿaymān with the subject of the person punished for drinking, see via WSASN: NSKXV05P143B and IHMAV12P370B; via the witness of WZATB (but not found in the redaction of Ibn Hishām) NSSXV04P415A,IHMAV12P370C, BQRXV03P340B, BQSXV08P545B, and BQMXV13P039A; via the witness of WYUAU, IBABV01P081B, BQSXV08P545A, and KHTSV04P307A; via WSACD: HBHXV32P210A; and via WHSSH: KHTSV04P307B and YNBHV12P358D. Without a witness, YNBHV12P358A. @EC_01/09/24@

